nodes.label: Distinguishing between categorical nominal and ordinal data
nodes.explanation: Classifying categorical data into nominal (no inherent order) and ordinal (with a meaningful order) types.

nodes.label: Distinguishing between numerical discrete and continuous data
nodes.explanation: Classifying numerical data as discrete (countable values) or continuous (any value within an interval).

nodes.label: Population and sample concepts
nodes.explanation: Understanding the difference between the entire group being studied (population) and a subset selected for analysis (sample).

nodes.label: Simple random sampling
nodes.explanation: Selecting a sample from a population such that every member has an equal chance of being chosen.

nodes.label: Stratified sampling
nodes.explanation: Dividing the population into subgroups (strata) and randomly sampling from each to ensure representation.

nodes.label: Cluster sampling
nodes.explanation: Dividing the population into clusters and randomly selecting entire clusters for the sample.

nodes.label: Quota sampling
nodes.explanation: Selecting a sample that reflects certain characteristics of the population by filling quotas for those characteristics.

nodes.label: Recognizing and avoiding biased samples
nodes.explanation: Identifying samples that do not fairly represent the population and understanding how to prevent such bias.

nodes.label: Randomisation in study design
nodes.explanation: Using random assignment to groups or treatments to reduce bias and ensure validity in experiments.

nodes.label: Role of control group in experiments
nodes.explanation: Using a group that does not receive the treatment to serve as a baseline for comparison in experiments.

nodes.label: Recognizing biases, limitations, and ethical issues in studies
nodes.explanation: Identifying potential sources of error, constraints, and ethical considerations in different types of statistical studies.

nodes.label: Formulating statistical questions
nodes.explanation: Creating clear, answerable questions that can be addressed using data analysis.

nodes.label: Collecting data from various sources
nodes.explanation: Gathering data through experiments, surveys, observational studies, or secondary sources such as the internet.

nodes.label: Summarizing data in diagrammatic form
nodes.explanation: Representing data visually using charts, plots, or spreadsheets to clarify patterns and findings.

nodes.label: Using pie charts for categorical data
nodes.explanation: Displaying proportions of categories as slices of a circle to show relative frequencies.

nodes.label: Using bar charts for categorical data
nodes.explanation: Representing categorical data with rectangular bars whose lengths are proportional to the category frequencies.

nodes.label: Using line plots for univariate data
nodes.explanation: Displaying data points along a number line to show frequency of values.

nodes.label: Using histograms with equal intervals
nodes.explanation: Representing numerical data by grouping values into equal-width intervals and displaying frequencies as bars.

nodes.label: Using stem-and-leaf plots
nodes.explanation: Organizing numerical data to show distribution while retaining original data values.

nodes.label: Using back-to-back stem-and-leaf plots for comparison
nodes.explanation: Displaying two related data sets side by side to compare their distributions.

nodes.label: Using scatterplots to determine relationships between variables
nodes.explanation: Plotting paired data points to visualize potential correlations or associations between two variables.

nodes.label: Correlation coefficient as measure of linear relationship
nodes.explanation: A numerical value between -1 and +1 that quantifies the strength and direction of a linear relationship between two variables.

nodes.label: Matching correlation coefficient values to scatterplots
nodes.explanation: Interpreting scatterplots to estimate the correlation coefficient and understand the strength of association.

nodes.label: Understanding that correlation does not imply causality
nodes.explanation: Recognizing that a statistical association between variables does not necessarily mean one causes the other.

nodes.label: Measures of variability: range
nodes.explanation: The difference between the maximum and minimum values in a data set.

nodes.label: Measures of variability: interquartile range (IQR)
nodes.explanation: The difference between the third quartile (Q3) and first quartile (Q1), representing the spread of the middle 50% of data.

nodes.label: Finding quartiles in a data set
nodes.explanation: Dividing ordered data into four equal parts to identify Q1, median (Q2), and Q3.

nodes.label: Calculating standard deviation
nodes.explanation: Measuring the average amount by which data values deviate from the mean, indicating spread or variability.

nodes.label: Recognizing outliers in data
nodes.explanation: Identifying data points that are significantly different from the majority of the data, often using IQR or standard deviation criteria.

nodes.label: Analyzing plots to explain differences in measures of center and spread
nodes.explanation: Interpreting graphical data displays to understand variations in central tendency and variability between data sets.

nodes.label: Drawing line of best fit by eye
nodes.explanation: Manually sketching a line through a scatterplot that best represents the trend of the data points.

nodes.label: Making predictions based on line of best fit
nodes.explanation: Using the line of best fit to estimate values of one variable given values of another.

nodes.label: Calculating correlation coefficient using a calculator
nodes.explanation: Using technology to compute the numerical measure of linear association between two variables.

nodes.label: Using percentiles to assign relative standing
nodes.explanation: Determining the position of a data value relative to the rest of the data by calculating the percentage of values below it.

nodes.label: Exploring distribution shape: symmetry and skewness
nodes.explanation: Describing the shape of data distributions by assessing whether data are symmetric or skewed to the left or right.

nodes.label: Relating sampling variability to population inference
nodes.explanation: Understanding how differences between samples affect the reliability of conclusions about the population.

nodes.label: Interpreting graphical summaries in context
nodes.explanation: Making sense of visual data representations by connecting them to the original question or problem.

nodes.label: use a variety of summary statistics to describe the data (mean, median, mode, range)
nodes.explanation: Concept referenced in relationship: use a variety of summary statistics to describe the data (mean, median, mode, range)
